folder: Henry Street & Market Street, Manhattan, NY
text:
(1) Henry Street, at, adjoining and west of the N.W. corner of Market Street, showing the presbyterian Church of the Sea and Land. This church was built in 1817 of stone with 3 foot walls, on the former Col. Henry Rutgers farm, and contains, behind the organ, a second gallery that was occupied by slaves. May 1924. Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(2) The same, showing the rooftops. Note the parish house, adjoining the church on the Henry Street side. June 1929. Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(3) A larger view showing solely the Church. About 1890. Gift of Samuel Landsman.

folder: Henry Street & Market Street, Manhattan, NY
text:
(1)
Henry Street, north side, west from Market to Oliver Streets, (where it terminates), showing the Presbyterian Church of the Sea and Land at the N.W. corner of Market Street and the parish house adjoining it. In the far background is shown the Municipal Building.
September 24, 1927.
P. L. Sperr.
(2)
The same, at a later date, including a view of the Woolworth Building.
July 9, 1932.
P. L. Sperr.  Note: A better print is located in NYC photo file under "Eastman Experimental Posts F - No. 5"
(3)
A portion of the same, showing a more comprehensive view of the parish house bearing No. 6l Henry Street. Also shown is a portion of the Manhattan Bridge.
September 5, 1927.
P. L. Sperr.

folder: Henry Street & Market Street, Manhattan, NY
text:
Federal Art Project
"Changing New York"
Berenice Abbott, photographer

Henry Street, west from Market to Oliver Street, as viewed from the Manhattan Bridge.  In the foreground is the Presbyterian Church of the Sea and Land.  The background is comprised of towering structures surrounding the civic center, Foley Square.  From right to left they are Transportation, Pulitzer (World), Tribune, Park Row, and Singer Buildings.

Neg. No. 227
[Note: negative at Museum of the City of New York]
Code I D
March 30, 1937

Note the organ and the organ loft in View 2. This is referred to as the slave balcony in various references to this structure.

Gift of Samuel Landsman

Unknown date
